Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Horton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Warwickshire): habitational name from one or other of the many places so called, such as those in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Dorset, Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Northamptonshire, Shropshire, Somerset, Staffordshire, Wiltshire, and Yorkshire. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>horh</i> or <i>horu</i> ‘dirt, filth’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some may have different origins, including Horton in Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":5,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":18,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":27,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Horton was born in 1310, in Stroud, Gloucestershire, England. She married Henry de Harding about 1338, in Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died on 9 February 1339, in Minster, Kent, England, at the age of 29, and was buried in Minster, Kent, England."},"et":{"1310–9 February 1339":"1310–9. veebruar 1339","1304–1372":"1304–1372","1349–1414":"1349–1414","–Male":"Surnud","1310–1339":"1310–1339","1372":"1372","9 February 1339":"9. veebruar 1339","1349":"1349","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1414":"1414","1304":"1304","about 1338":"umbes 1338","1310":"1310","1453":"1453","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","1339":"1339","Stroud, Gloucestershire, England":"Stroud, Gloucestershire, England","Minster, Kent, England":"Minster, Kent, England","Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1310–9 February 1339":"1310–9. helmikuuta 1339","1304–1372":"1304–1372","1349–1414":"1349–1414","–Male":"Kuollut","1310–1339":"1310–1339","1372":"1372","9 February 1339":"9. helmikuuta 1339","1349":"13